Embeddings live in a typed column. The column declares its dimension ahead of time: vector(768) for SBERT, 3072 for text-embedding-3-large. Similarity queries use one of three distance operators. Cosine distance is the middle dot operator written as `<=>` in SQL. Example:
ALTER TABLE docs ADD COLUMN embedding vector(768);
SELECT id, text FROM docs ORDER BY embedding <=> query_embedding LIMIT 10;
Three operators: `<=>` Cosine (default for text embeddings), `<->` L2 Euclidean (some vision embeddings), `<#>` negative inner product (normalized + fast). Cosine is default because SBERT-family embeddings are direction-carriers, not magnitude-carriers.

Without an index, ORDER BY ... <=> ... does brute-force search over every row. For production create an index: HNSW (graph, better recall, slower build) or IVFFlat (cluster probe, faster build, lower memory). HNSW params: m = 16, ef_construction = 64, ef_search = 40 - better recall + latency, slower to build. IVFFlat params: lists = sqrt(N), probes = sqrt(lists), fast to build, smaller memory, needs tuning per size. Create index SQL:
CREATE INDEX ON docs USING hnsw (embedding vector_cosine_ops) WITH (m = 16, ef_construction = 64);
SET hnsw.ef_search = 40;
Tuning is SQL. Logging, query planning, and EXPLAIN ANALYZE work the same as any other Postgres index.

The hidden payoff: vectors live next to existing rows, so you can join, filter, transact, and query metadata in SQL you already write. Other vector DBs bolt on filtering and joins; Postgres always had them. Inherited features: Transactions + ACID (insert row and vector in one atomic write), SQL joins (join docs to users to permissions to embeddings in one query), rich metadata queries (GIN indexes on JSONB, partial indexes, window functions), existing ops (backups, WAL replication, monitoring, PITR already in place). Compound query example on cat corpus:
SELECT d.id, d.text, u.name FROM docs d JOIN users u ON u.id = d.owner_id WHERE u.tenant_id = 42 ORDER BY d.embedding <=> query_embedding LIMIT 10;
One query covers similarity search, metadata filtering (tenant_id), and a join to users. Other vector DBs need multiple systems or extra services to do this.
